<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-05-21T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-05-21T04:00:00-05:00" n="67" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d67">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/10451: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-05-21T17:00:00+08:00">May 21, 1929—5
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received May 22—8:30 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>408. My 394, May 17, 6 p.m.<note n="41" xml:id="d67fn41">Not
                                printed.</note> Following from American Consul at Tsingtao: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“May 21, 11 a.m. Japanese evacuation of Shantung completed
                                    according to schedule when last troops and General Yasumitsu
                                    sailed from Tsingtao yesterday. Five hundred marines from the
                                    Chinese warship <hi rend="italic">Chenhai</hi> landed morning of
                                    20th to cooperate with Government officers of peace and order
                                    already here. City tranquil, and no symptom of disorders
                                    apparent.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>